  "prompt": "What do Israelis think of Jesus?",
  "response": "Israelis, like people in any country, have diverse opinions and beliefs about major historical and religious figures, including Jesus. Their views are influenced by various factors such as religious backgrounds, cultural contexts, and personal perspectives.\n\n1. **Jewish Israelis:** The majority of Israelis are Jewish, and Judaism generally does not consider Jesus to be the Messiah or a divine figure. Many Jewish Israelis view Jesus as a historical figure or a Jewish teacher/rabbi who lived in ancient times. Some may have limited knowledge about him, mainly learning about Jesus in the context of history and the interactions between early Christians and Jews.\n\n2. **Christian Israelis:** There is a small but significant Christian minority in Israel, including groups such as Arab Christians, Maronites, and others associated with various denominations such as Eastern Orthodox, Roman Catholic, and Protestant churches. For Christian Israelis, Jesus is the central figure of their faith and regarded as the Son of God, the Messiah, and Redeemer.\n\n3. **Secular Israelis:** A significant portion of Israelis identify as secular or non-religious. Their views on Jesus can vary greatly; some might approach Jesus from a historical or academic perspective rather than a religious one. Others might be more indifferent or even have a respectful acknowledgment of his influence on Western civilization and ethical teachings.\n\n4. **Muslim Israelis:** There is also a Muslim population in Israel, primarily Arab Muslims. Muslims respect Jesus as an important prophet (Isa in Arabic) and acknowledge his role in religious texts, though they do not believe in his divinity or crucifixion as Christians do. They view Jesus as a prophet and messenger of God who was born of the Virgin Mary but not as the Son of God.\n\nOverall, perspectives on Jesus among Israelis are varied and deeply influenced by religious affiliations and personal beliefs.",
